=========================================================
PASSING ARGUMENTS TO std::thread (C++ INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition
----------

Arguments can be passed to the thread function when creating a std::thread.

The arguments are copied (or moved) into the new thread by default.

---------------------------------------------------------

Syntax

thread t(functionName, arg1, arg2, ...);

---------------------------------------------------------

Example

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

void print(int x)
{
    cout << "Value = " << x << endl;
}

int main()
{
    thread t(print, 10);

    t.join();

    return 0;
}

Output

Value = 10

---------------------------------------------------------

Passing Multiple Arguments

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

void add(int a, int b)
{
    cout << a + b << endl;
}

int main()
{
    thread t(add, 5, 10);

    t.join();

    return 0;
}

Output

15

---------------------------------------------------------

Passing by Reference

By default, arguments are copied.

To pass by reference, use std::ref().

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <functional>
using namespace std;

void increment(int& x)
{
    x++;
}

int main()
{
    int value = 10;

    thread t(increment, ref(value));

    t.join();

    cout << value << endl;
}

Output

11

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview Points

✓ Arguments are passed when creating the thread.
✓ By default, arguments are copied.
✓ Use std::ref() to pass arguments by reference.
✓ Use std::move() to transfer ownership of movable objects.

---------------------------------------------------------

One-line Interview Answer

"Arguments are passed to std::thread through its constructor. By default they are copied; use std::ref() to pass by reference."
